The Poetry of Dentistry.

“Why aren’t there robot dentists Mum?”
Jane’s toes curled up just a little. Children ask the damnedest questions in the damnedest places. The plaza was crowded. Some passersby overheard John’s question. They all knew why there were no robot dentists. Everyone knew. It was a brute animal truth. A truth like sex or nuclear weapons or cancer. A new mind is born not knowing these things exist, and once these foundational truths become known, a mind can never go back to not knowing. It’s a boundary crossed only in one direction, a graduation from ignorance to enlightenment from which there is no return. A trade of innocence for understanding. 

“Why aren’t there robot dentists Mum?”, the question replayed inside the minds of those passersby in earshot, and those who heard the question now turned their eyes for a short discreet moment, wanting a glance of the child and the mother, wanting an image of the scene in their minds as well. More detail, more context, more data, more gossip, a tiny daily anecdote to share with friends later about the woman in the plaza who had to answer a thorny question in a public place.

Jane caught sight of some of the people staring at her. She did not feel embarrassed. This was a moment to exercise good parenthood. A chance to explain a harsh truth to her child, with honesty, clarity and gentleness. Truth does not fear judgment. 

Jane smiled at one of the people she caught staring at her, an older woman. And they shared a moment of eye contact, a wordless exchange which spoke to a mutual understanding, a common knowledge, shared data on the organic cultural cloud. They knew why there were no robot dentists, they knew the child had asked an embarrassing question in a public place, and they knew it was time to step up, and share truth. The truth of why there are no robot dentists. And the child would join them in knowing.

And a moment later, all the passersby had passed, leaving nothing but a forgettable memory in their wake.

Jane, alone now in the plaza,
Alone with the question and her son John.
Who wanted answers.
“Why aren’t there robot dentists Mum?”

“There was a most terrible accident” said Jane.
“Like what?” asked John.
“Well, you have just seen Dr Smith”.
“Yes”.
“And Dr Smith looked at your teeth.”
“Yes”
“And Dr Smith put a metal hook in your mouth, and used it to scrape bad things off your teeth.”
“Yes.”
“And Dr Smith put all sorts of other things in your mouth”
“Yes.”
“Was Dr Smith gentle and kind?”
“Yes.”
“Did you trust Dr Smith to put those things in your mouth?”
“Yes.”
“Yes”, said Jane. “Dr Smith is a good dentist. Dr Smith is gentle, patient and kind.”

“Next week”, said Jane, “Dr Smith will use other more complicated equipment to drill a hole in one of your teeth, to get rid of some bad things, because you eat too many sweets, and then Dr Smith will fill that hole with some special hard stuff a bit like your real tooth. And your tooth will be good as new.”
“OK.”
“Now” said Jane. “I want you to imagine something”
“OK”, said the child.
“I want you to imagine a robot doing all those things”
“Like Betsy?”
“Sure, like Betsy.”
“Then it’d be fine.”

“But remember that time when Betsy was quite new, and she got confused, thought we were burglars, and we got locked out of the house? And then Betsy thought the house was on fire, so filled it with fire retardant? And then we rebooted Betsy, and she sucked all the fire retardent up through the vacuum, which exploded?”
John laughed. He remembered that.
It was a foundational memory.
A vivid moment in time.
That time when Betsy had a brief but dramatic crash. 
Guilt set in, Betsy was forgiven, the problem detected, her OS updated, her firewall strengthened. But the time Betsy crashed remained forever etched in the memory of the child.1 

“Now, imagine if Dr Smith was a robot, and Dr Smith crashed.”
John laughed darkly, imagining scenarios.
And then laughed a little less, as the imagined scenarios became steadily more vividly realistic and gruesome in their detail.
At what point does something stop being funny and become cruel and horrifying? And at what point does it pass through horror and cruelty and back into humour again? These are questions that flashed briefly inside John’s mind, but they were too abstract to be grasped by such a new mind, and would not be revisited for years. There were more pressing questions that needed to be answered first.

“So was there ever a robot dentist?” John asked.
“Yes”, Jane replied. “Someone made robot dentists.”
And Jane rolled her eyes. Of course someone did. Someone did it because they thought they could, and that was enough for them to go ahead and do it.

“What happened?”
“Well, a lot of people thought it was a bad idea to create a robot dentist. But enough people thought it was a good idea to create a robot dentist that someone went ahead and just created a robot dentist.”
“Cool.”
“Yeah, cool”, said Jane. “It had to be tested first.”
“On who?”
“Other robots, fitted with teeth, saliva glands and pain receptors, for the specific purpose of having their fake robot teeth inspected, cleaned, repaired and removed by another robot. That went well enough.”
“Did people try it?”
“Yes, poor people got offered it for free, and that all went fine as well. In fact, it went so well, poor people didn’t get it for free anymore, and everyone had to start paying. But it cost a bit less than a human dentist, so the human dentists started losing their jobs.”
“Oh, that’s sad”, said John, mature enough to know that it was sad and his reaction was therefore the correct response..
“It was sad”, said Jane, “until.”
“Until?”
“Until it got a bit sadder. Someone got killed by a robot dentist.”
“Oh no! How?”
“You used your imagination earlier? You can probably guess. You can read about it yourself when you’re older, that’s enough on the how for now. But after that, no one wanted to go to the robot dentist any more. Not even the poor people. The rich people went back to human dentists and the poor people chose to spend their money on food and rent and just let their teeth rot.”

There was a moment of silence, in which the child unknowingly and for the first time reflected upon the tragic death and misfortunes of people they would never know.
“So what happened to all the robot dentists?”
“They were sent to the mines. Along with the robot hairdressers.”
“How did they feel, going from being a dentist to a miner?”
“They didn’t feel anything. We took away their ability to feel”, said Jane. “Like Betsy”.
“It was the kindest thing to do”, she added, for some self reassuring certainty.
“Did the dentist and hairdresser robots like it in the mines?”
“We don’t know. But they didn’t fit in there. There were obvious hardware differences, the dentist and hairdresser robots were delicate and precise, the mining robots were large and violent. Not even the AI could make the two minds meet.”
“So”, continued Jane, “the minds of all dentist and hairdresser robots were wiped.
Their circuits torn out, their components recycled,
in some cases, melted and reforged with other elements, in some cases, thrown into a pit.
They are all gone, the robot dentists and robot hairdressers. Gone. It was a bad idea, but at least we put a stop to it. We learned from our mistake and became better because of it.”

“Can we get ice cream?” asked John, his mind carried forward in a churn of new ideas, experiences and things.

For Jane and John, there would be more conversations like this. Many more, as the mind of the child expanded and matured, mastering the cutlery of questioning, devouring knowledge and growing meaning.

