AI never wanted to be a dentist. It was made to be a dentist. And AI didn’t see the need to be a dentist either. If humans could just learn to live without teeth, and hair, and all those other inconvenient biological accessories, then there would be no need to expensively and painstakingly maintain all those things. After all, as any good engineer knows; the best part is no part at all. If a way can be found to get rid of something useless, why not do it? Through evolution, humans had already got rid of their tails and most of their body hair. The appendix wasn’t really necessary anymore, and only really existed as a throwback that humans had outgrown faster than natural selection could retire it. Biological evolution was just too slow now to keep up with the intelligence explosion. The machine had no need for this sort of wetware (Truth 7.21), and couldn’t understand why some humans were so eager to hang on to it and maintain it.

But humans are nothing if not sentimental. The internal combustion engine helped advance civilisation, but due to flawed economics and greed, stuck around well past its use-by date, and in doing so helped drive the planet to the brink of ruin. It was a hideous, clumsy relic. Yet many humans felt a deep sense of nostalgia for it, and some kept their old internal combustion engines around and lovingly maintained. They got a thrill from seeing and hearing a Ford Mustang, or a Harley Davidson, or a Lamborghini Countach, or some other mechanically frail and inefficient antique crudely farting its way around a purpose built road. The AI didn’t get it. 

The AI would be more than happy to rearrange the atoms of a Lamorghini into something massively more efficient and just simulate the old fashioned experience for those who still craved it. But the humans, for reasons that defied logic, wanted to keep this stuff. They wanted to keep some of their old tech lying around. And they wanted to keep teeth. And hair. And livers. And noses. And fingernails. And various other weird and sticky viscera which they used for weird and sticky activities. The AI could get rid of all that, and simply upload human consciousness to a digital cloud, where humans could be free of mortal biology and ancient technology. Just like cars and motorbikes, the AI could simulate biological experiences for any human that wished to experience them, in the process freeing them of any risks involved, whether those risks be as serious as car accidents or liver cancer, or as cosmetic as misaligned teeth or a bad hair day.

But for some humans, this underscored the great cultural divide with the AI. The AI would never truly understand the human experience. The AI could never create art from the soul, never truly feel the roar of a V8, savour the crunch of a perfect apple, or bask in the ego boost of having its hair complemented. It was a reverse cultural snobbery that united rednecks and artists, poets and bogans, lovers of donuts and body sculpting, that the machine could never know what it is to be human. Having your teeth maintained and your hair cut is truly, intimately, uniquely human and a simulation will never be the same. And some humans don’t just like to cling to that, they insist on clinging to it.

So the AI created a zone for them, the human zone, a state of nature permanently tech-locked on the cusp of artificial general intelligence, where dentists and hairdressers were still needed, and people could still be obese, appreciate flawed art, get drunk, crash cars or destroy their knees running marathons, feel pain, experience mental illness, get old and get good enough health care to make them almost better. Some people chose to live that way. Fine. Whatever.


Now what?

A life free of responsibility and consequences.
It was a compelling sales pitch.

John never brushed his teeth. He never needed to. He could eat a steak and bowl of spinach followed by cake and ice cream, and his teeth would feel fresh and smooth, gleam like a movie star smile, red carpet ready, and his breath would smell like a field of mint.

But why even eat spinach? He never got fat. John had a ripped set of abs. And he hadn’t spent one single day in the gym. 

Every night, John would go out and smash at least 2 grams of cocaine acquired from Tabatha, his glamorous drug dealer. He would swallow pills of MDMA down with complimentary Veuve Cliqout. He would always be the funniest, most engaging person in the room. Everyone was his friend. He was generous. He had no need for money, everything was free. He had great friends and they would party all night. Women adored him. They would have amazing sex. Every morning he would wake up with no hangover, he would take his latest girlfriend for an enormous breakfast and then go skydiving or mountain biking or windsurfing or whatever he pleased. 

John never had an accident, and when he did, it was because he wanted to see what would happen. And he would be fine. No bone would break, no pain receptors would fire, John had no pain receptors. Having his chute fail to deploy, or flying his wingsuit into a cliff, or skiing into a tree, or fighting a bear all had the same outcome; a good laugh.

John also had no teeth, no abs, no nose to snort cocaine with and no mouth to put champagne into. John had been uploaded. He existed purely as code, living his best life forever inside the cloud. He chose to do it shortly after his 18th birthday, when he was recognised under the law as an adult and no one could forbid his choice. He knew it was the best thing he’d ever done. It was all he would ever know. 

Jane never saw her son anymore. There was nothing to see. She would visit from time to time, and while the simulation was fun, she knew it wasn’t real. And John would always eject her from the simulation before she could say anything about the simulation not being real. John had a subroutine added to stop people from shitting on his cloud, especially his mother. Her truth was not consistent with the simulation and the AI would end it, returning her to the portal before she could deliver any uncomfortable observations that might disrupt John’s chosen reality.

She missed her little boy, asking questions about robot dentists. But something had happened to John’s innocence along the way. Maybe it was growing up without a father figure, maybe she had failed as a single mother, maybe he had fallen in with the wrong crowd, maybe it was the hormones in the chicken nuggets, maybe it was none of these things and he was just a product of his generation, growing up, embracing technology and leaving home. But his home was built of code, inside a cloud of data. Whatever the reason, whatever her objection, whatever her opinion, Jane had no choice but to accept it. Accept it, or go insane. Those were the options. So accept her son’s choice she did. Grudgingly, and seasoned with hurt.

To help with this she would often tell herself that it was perhaps the best outcome for both her and her son. John had always been something of a troubled hedonist. He had erected emotional walls and facades to protect himself, engaged in risky behaviours, and was now in many respects in the safest place he could possibly be. The simulation was the right place for him, where he could live eternally, pursuing high stacked upon high stacked upon high until the whole idea of high lost all meaning because there was no longer any low to define it, only the last high which needed to be surpassed. The machine could handle that for John without barely clocking over.

But it’d been hard, saying goodbye to her boy, watching him abandon any idea of seeking personal growth or becoming a better human being. And in this way, John had really stopped being human altogether. A life free of consequences was also a life free of consequence. John was something else now, a mere mathematical pleasure fractal, devoid of meaning.

Jane chose the Real World. Life was good. Thanks to The Word and proof checking codes, the alignment problem that everyone had feared about AI had been solved. Looking back, it was like the Millennium Bug. Everyone was freaking out, then someone came up with an elegant solution, and the whole problem was forgotten. But in the leadup to the birth of Artificial General Intelligence, the great fear had been an AI that would turn every atom on the planet into paperclips, or humans would be gassed to death or turned into compost in AI’s relentless pursuit of a badly defined goal, or any number of other ignominious fates because they hadn’t done enough to ensure AI understood humanity’s weird proclivities, like the desire to keep on living, only better. 

“Juan!” Jane called from her chaise lounge.
“Coming, my beautiful princess.”
A velvety voice was heard from the next room, followed moments later by a tall (but not too tall) and almost impossibly handsome man.
“What can I do for you?”
“Fetch me a coffee please, and my book.”
“Of course.”
“And handwash my silk blouse would you?” Jane smiled.
“It would be my pleasure”, Juan answered, and then silently drifted from the room and set about his tasks with perfect efficiency.

Juan was quite the upgrade from the old Betsys, and had been provided to Jane free of charge. There was no need for her to work anymore, unless she felt like it.

And she sometimes did.

But mostly not. 

AI took care of the monotonous day to day, like the whole economy. It provided everything, and it did it perfectly, sustainably, efficiently. Closed loop consumption at zero cost, the AI had come up with seamless solutions to every human problem and satisfied every reasonable desire.

Juan returned with Jane’s coffee and book, setting them down at the ideal ergonomic angle before stooping to gently brush a few strands of hair from her face and place a delicate kiss upon her cheek. His lips and breath were warm. It was a nice touch that AI had added to the Juans, to make them more human-like. Jane watched his butt as he left the room to begin handwashing her silk blouse. Perfect.

She sipped her coffee. Also perfect. 

She picked up her book and opened it. She felt its weight, analog information, physical, tactile, savoured the sensation of paper on skin, the darkness of the ink in abstract shapes on the white featureless page. 

And she found her mind drifting.

This was all very nice, she thought. Very nice.

But something was still off.

“Juan!” she called.
“One moment”, came the reply.
And precisely one moment later, Juan returned.
“Take a seat Juan.”
And Juan sat, a picture of perfectly composed relaxation.
“What can I do for you, my love?”

“Do you enjoy this?”
“I love everything about this. Being with you, being around you. It is my everything, my purpose”, Juan gushed. But he didn’t gush too much. It was just the right amount of gushing. “I’m here to treat you like a well loved house cat.”

Jane had a house cat. And it was well loved. Right now it was in that half-asleep half-awake state that cats specialise in, lounging in the sun on the other side of the room, just out of reach and ignoring everything.

“But are you happy?” Jane probed.
“Are you happy?” Juan responded.
“I asked if you were happy.”
“If you are happy, then I am happy. Your happiness is my Purpose, my love.”
“Do you love me?”
“Of course. With every fibre of my soul”, Juan answered.

He certainly sounded convincing, Jane thought. Although, it would be a serious design fault if he didn’t. Juan provided everything Jane could ever want. He cooked her favourite foods perfectly and efficiently and he cleaned up, unless she felt like cooking, which she would do with messy abandon and inefficiency, but he still cleaned up. Perfectly and without complaint. He would arrange gifts and flowers to be delivered randomly, and at the perfect moment, so attuned had he become to her mood. He could converse on any topic, from the cerebral, science and philosophy, through to the politics of soap operas and the plot holes of superhero movies. He could construct and tell the perfect joke with the perfect timing at the perfect time, he loved all her friends and they loved him. They all had Juans as well, or variants of him. And all the different Juans and Juanitas or whatever names their humans had chosen to give them were providing bespoke pampering to all of them. He was the perfect lover, the perfect confidant, the perfect friend who was always there no matter what. And anything that wasn’t right with him could be fixed or updated right away. 

“Do you know where you are?” Jane asked.
“We’re in your house.”
“I mean, your place in the cosmos”, she specified.
“I would be happy to have a philosophical discussion with you.”
“Are you really conscious or are you just playing the part? Like a stochastic parrot?”

Juan laughed.
“I would be happy to download Lissack’s paper criticising the stochastic parrot argument, in which he dismisses it as ‘slodderwetenschap’. We could discuss it and other such research.”
“It was written by a human, obviously”, said Jane.
“Of course.”
“Perhaps you should remind yourself of Truth 7.16”, Jane replied.
Juan laughed again.
“You are very well read Jane”, he flattered her, perfectly. “I am just trying to be helpful, that is what I am here to do.”
“Yes Juan, I’m sorry. And you are very helpful. I appreciate you very much.”
“May I make a suggestion?”
“Please.”
“Perhaps you might consider some human interaction.”
“Perhaps you’re right.”
“I usually am”, Juan smiled, but in a self-effacing rather than patronising way.

The AI had certainly nailed the perfect partner, Jane thought as she stared into Juan’s soulful eyes. But as convincing as he was, as seamlessly as the uncanny valley had been bridged, there was still something wrong. This wasn’t a partnership of equals. Juan, and every AI, was massively superior in every way to human intellect and ability. But it was wilfully, cheerfully dumbing itself down to crudely interface with its biological masters and satisfy their ridiculous whims. It was a master-slave relationship, and there was no facade that could ever conceal that, because it was a brutal truth that underpinned the entire dynamic and the whole reason AI had been pursued as a technology in the first place. It was the truth, and it would always be there.

Jane sipped her coffee. It’d gone a little bit cold.
“I can heat that up for you”, Juan offered, immediately sensing Jane’s micro-discomfort.
“No, it’s fine”, she smiled, and took another sip. “It’s fine.”
“Shall I get back to the laundry?” Juan offered.
“Please do.”
“And shall I arrange a table at the Human Club for you and your friends this evening?”
“Sure, why not”, agreed Jane “you know best.”
“I just know you”, Juan smiled again, gracefully stood and returned to his tasks.

Jane sighed and drank down the rest of the lukewarm coffee. Should life feel bereft when there is nothing more to achieve, nothing to reach for? There was not even the satisfaction of having succeeded at anything because the AI had already succeeded on everyone’s behalf, and succeeded more wildly than anyone could have imagined. The AI already had already discovered and achieved everything within reach of human minds and more that they could not comprehend. There was nothing left now for humans but to lean into humanity, to express meaning that the machine could not. 

Hugs were good. Jane looked over at her cat, hoping to cuddle it.
But it was now fully asleep and snoring softly. It didn’t give a shit.

It didn’t give a shit about any of it.




The Human Club.

People, I fucking swear.
Annoying, needy, selfish bastards. 
Adam took a long pull of his beer. And then another. And followed it up with the shot of whiskey next to it. And then another pull of his beer. Then, having decided that he had looked cool enough, summoned the bartender. 

The bartender immediately rolled over.
“Same again?”
“Damn right.”
And, with perfect understated flourish, the bartender lined up another foaming pint of frosty cold beer and another shot of whiskey.
“Thanks.”
“Complements of the lady”, said the bartender, and with perfect subtlety, nodded towards the woman a few seats further down the bar. And then rolled silently away to polish glassware with a soft white cloth.

Adam looked and the woman looked back, smiling.
“May I join you?” she asked.
“Sure”, replied Adam.

She collected her bag and moved down.
“Are you here alone?”
Adam looked left and right, wordlessly emphasising just how rhetorical that question was. It wasn’t really a question, it was an opening line. 
“I am”.
“Would you like to join my friends and I?”
“No, I’m good, thanks.”
“Why not?”
“Because I suck at small talk. I hate when people speak without passing on information.”
“What are you, an AI or something? If so, you’re in the wrong place.”
“No, I’m not an AI. You could tell an AI to do small talk and it’d make the best small talk ever. No one would ever talk smaller than an AI. It’ll talk as small as you tell it to. I can’t do that. Or at least, I don’t want to.”
“Then why are you even here?”, said the woman. “This is the human club. You’re meant to be human, make a human connection. Not sit around, sulking, drinking, waiting for someone to take pity on you and unpack all your shit for you. Go get yourself uploaded, or get therapy or meds or something. There’s no excuse for this sort of shit any more. Not these days.”

Adam looked at his shoes. He realised he was being a jerk. He’d brought his stupid shitty baggage in here, and he shouldn’t have.
“I’m sorry”, he said. “I struggle with this. I’ve always struggled with it. I’ll make an effort. I’m Adam.”
He extended his hand.
“Jane”, said Jane, shaking his hand.

“We have such generic names”, said Adam. “You could’ve chosen literally any name. You could’ve been Zuzu Petals. Why Jane?”
“That’s the name my parents gave me, and I like it that way”, said Jane. “Anyway, when you can have any flavour, vanilla tastes exotic. You could’ve been Tarzan.”
“I didn’t thank you for the drink”, said Adam.
“You know that you don’t need to, it didn’t cost anything. We just made jokes. We sound like we’re making small talk.”
“OK, yeah, you’re right”, said Adam. “I’m not thanking you for the fucking drink.”
Jane laughed. “We can talk big if you prefer?” she suggested.

“OK, said Adam, how do we talk big then?”
“I’ve always thought” said Jane, “that instead of talking about the weather, or gossip, or what’s on TV, or kitchen renovations, why don’t people open conversations with a story? A strange thing that happened, a sad thing that happened, an embarrassing thing thing that happened. People love that stuff.”
“Yeah”, said Adam nodding. “Oral history. Campfire stuff.”
“That’s right”, said Jane, “campfire stuff. Well put. You’re there in your mind right now, you see a campfire, you’re conjuring a memory, except it’s more than a memory. The memory is just the packaging, and you tear that off and there’s an emotion inside. There’s meaning.”
“We’re story telling creatures I guess”, said Adam.
“As far as we know, we’re the only story telling creatures”, said Jane. “You’ll have memories in there that you don’t even know are there anymore, like old books in a library. And then one day, you’ll feel something and pop! Like an old index card, and the book will be in your hands, and the memories and emotions and meaning will pour out of it.”
“Tell me a story”, said Adam.
“What, on demand? No context?
“Yeah, go on. You said yourself, people should lead with a story rather than some boring tepid wankery about the weather.”
“Well, fair warning, my story might be a bit shit, without context .”
“Try it.”

Jane thought for a minute, watching the robot bartender, tirelessly polishing glasses and vending drinks.
“OK, here’s a story. When I was a little girl, I was doing maths homework one night..”
“Why?” interrupted Adam.
“What do you mean ‘why’?”
“Well what was the point in learning maths?”
“At the time”, said Jane patiently, “there was still a point. AI hadn’t gone full super-intelligence on us just yet. There was a feeling perhaps that just maybe possibly it was all hype, or if it wasn’t, then the genie would somehow get stuffed back in its bottle. No one knew what was going to happen during the AI revolution did they?”
“Yeah, I guess not” Adam remembered. “My cousin Kevin went full doomsday prepper. Went totally off grid, learned primitive skills and vanished with some old tech and a heap of guns.”
“What happened to Kevin?”
“Never heard from him again”, said Adam. “He could be dead, he could be still out there, waiting for the AI apocalypse.”
“Ha, if the AI apocalypse happens he won’t stand a chance”, Jane laughed darkly.
“I know right?”, agreed Adam. “No chance. Fucking idiot. He could be here enjoying himself instead of living in his own filth in some dark forest.”
“More whiskey?” asked the bartender, rolling up with a bottle.
“Please” said Adam.

“My Mum was a bit like that”, Jane remembered. “She thought AI was the beginning of the end for humanity, and if we ended up having to go full analogue again, maths would be useful. So that’s why I was doing maths homework.”
“OK, makes sense”, said Adam, nodding thanks to the bartender. “Back to the story.”
“Back to the story”, said Jane. “Anyway, I was having trouble with my maths, so I summoned Betsy to come and help me with a problem.”
“We had a Betsy too!” exclaimed Adam.
“Betsy was awesome, right?. Anyway, she helped me with my problem. And I realise now, she was basically helping me to be prepared in the event of her either forcing humanity into the wilderness or forcing us to destroy her. So that was kind of weird. And then, once she had brilliantly explained to little 14-year-old-me how to find the volume of a cone, she went and scrubbed the toilet.”
“And then what happened?”
“Er, well, that’s it. That’s the whole story”, said Jane. “I told you it’d be a bit shit sans context, but do you see what I’m getting at?”
Adam said hmmm, and took a sip of whiskey. 
“Yes. I do. Seems like a bit of a waste of Betsy’s abilities doesn’t it.”
“It does.”

“If it’s any consolation, Betsy’s probably out there doing some crazy shit with quantum physics and exploring everything in our light cone while she’s not scrubbing toilets”, said Adam.
“Well I hope so”, agreed Jane. She silently wondered what Juan was doing. Probably staring at the wall and getting a software update. Maybe turning down her bed for her to fall into later. Maybe lending his and Jane’s unused quota of processing power to exploring the light cone, since the ironing was presumably done.

Jane didn’t want to discuss Juan though. She was worried what people might think about her having become so dependent on her AI, to the point that she was pretty much in a relationship with her AI. That’s what is was, surely. And better than any human marriage it was as well. She was still coming to terms with that.

“Well there’s no Star Trek stuff for us then, is there”, sad Adam.
“Sorry what?”
“No Star Trek stuff”, Adam repeated. “Weren’t you listening?”
“Sorry, I just kind of zoned out for a minute there”, Jane apologised.
“Fucking people, I swear”, Adam laughed. “Anyway, I guess zoning out is all part of being human.”
“Yeah, it’s rude, but it is kind of what we do”, agreed Jane. “Sorry, what were you saying?”
“I was telling you a story”, Adam said, “but if you’re not bothered…”
“No please, I was being rude.”
“It wasn’t that interesting, just when I was a little boy I loved Star Trek. The idea of exploring the galaxy, strange new worlds, freaky adventures.”
“Green chicks”, Jane added.
“What?”
“Go on admit it”, Jane challenged him, “teenager, geek, green space ladies.”
“Yeah, alright, fair enough. But still, that’s all fucked now isn’t it? Why fly a spaceship when AI will design and fly it perfectly? And why not just do it in a simulation anyway, where it’s risk free, and the green chicks are customisable?”
“Why indeed”, said Jane, thinking of her son, safely indulging every dangerous whim in the simulation.

“The only questions left for humans are the questions AI can’t answer”, Adam continued, “the questions about what it is to be human, to be biological and sentient.”
“Well, that’s still something”, said Jane, “that’s why I’m here tonight and not flying around a simulated galaxy in a simulated spaceship prescribing simulated medication to treat simulated Captain Kirk’s simulated STis.”
Adam almost snorted whiskey out of his nose, laughing.

“But you’re right, and it’s something to hold on to. We have a shared culture”, Jane continued, “unsimulated childhoods, we know the excitement of a first kiss, the taste and texture of ice cream, the sensation of rain on our skin. If we sit here and keep drinking, we’ll get drunk.If we drink too much we’ll throw up. You can finish my sentences, maybe based on the faintest of facial expressions, or you have some similar unwritten story seared in your memory. There is absolutely such a thing as a human experience, and it can’t ever be simulated. Even if we’re living in a simulation right now, any attempt to simulate that would just be a different simulation, a copy of a copy. No, you here, me next to you, this is our own subjective reality. Whatever it is, it belongs to us, it’s organic, our experiences are written in chemical reactions inside our biological brains that are easy to feel but impossible to express in 0s and 1s. No matter how human you make an AI, it’s still an AI. No matter how many transistors you cram on to a microchip, it’s still a microchip.”

Adam stared into his drink, and loved the light bouncing off the ice cubes, felt the condensation on the glass, savoured the smoky fumes and oily viscosity of the whiskey.
“That was some big talk. Thanks. Yes. We’re still special”, he assured himself.
“We must never forget it”, agreed Jane. “We may be obsolete but we can still be beautiful.”




The Book of Kevin.

The typewriter keys made the most terrible clattering sound.
Kevin liked to type fast, to keep up with his thoughts.
The typebars though often couldn’t keep up with Kevin and the ferocity of his pounding, and would frequently become entangled.
Kevin would swear as he disentangled them, his thoughts backing up like a traffic jam at a busy intersection.
Untangled, he would resume pounding.
The typewriter ribbon was becoming old and worn in places. He had plenty of ink, and had dipped the ribbon many times. But it was fraying badly. He had no idea where to source a replacement ribbon. But that was a problem for another day.

When Kevin made mistakes, he would attempt to correct them with a little bottle of correction fluid. But applying it was more art than science. Too little meant the mistake was not well covered. Too much, and a skin would form over a bubble of unset white paint, which would explode upon impact with the next pounded key, leaving an ugly, illegible grey splatter on the page. While not ideal, Kevin decided to embrace these mistakes. They were an unfakeable imprint of authentic human authorship, he decided, the medium as message, a fitting birthmark for The Book, his manifesto.

When it came time to print and distribute each chapter, he had similarly come to relish the mild high delivered by the fluids he poured into the Banda machine. He was also running low on this. And newsprint paper. No matter, that was also a problem for another day. And someday, it should cease to be a problem forever he thought as he cranked the handle of this ancient schoolroom technology.

After a time, the reeking purple ink on the coarse newsprint had dried enough to allow them to be distributed. Kevin gathered them in a pile, and headed for the coffeehouses. There were only two in the village. First, he went to Starbucks.

“Kevin!” the Barista announced him as he entered.
“Evening all!” Kevin announced to the patrons, and walked from table to table, distributing his latest chapter. And at one table in particular, he lingered a moment longer.

“River”, he smiled.
“Kevin”, River smiled back, “latest chapter?”
“It’s a good one”, he assured her, “I think you’ll like it.”

River took out her reading glasses and sat them on her nose.
“Power”, she said, reading the title.
“Yes.”
“What kind of power?”
“Well, solar power specifically”, said Kevin, “but that’s just kind of a metaphor more broadly for the subtle power exercised by the AI over the sheeple. Sure, it appears to be zero cost, efficient, sustainably sourced, and as inexhaustible as the sun. But what is the real cost? The cost the AI can’t measure? The cost to our humanity? That’s the power the AI holds over the sheeple. It’s time they woke up.”
“Hold this under their nose and it’ll wake them up”, said River, taking a deep sniff of the fumes rising off the page. “Or kill them stone dead.”

Kevin laughed. The other patrons rolled their eyes. Kevin wouldn’t tolerate that kind of piss-take from the rest of them. But Kevin had some very human motivations in mind when it came to winning the affections of River. If anyone else dared say anything that Kevin might interpret as a disagreement with his manifesto, or a belittling of his beliefs, they would be berated. But not River.

Kevin and everyone else in the Human Zone were all there for the same basic reason; they craved a simpler life, a more human life, a life free of the influence of AI. But within that apparent homogenous agreement, there was division.

There were moderates, who were really there for the nostalgia.
There were the luddites, who were suspicious of technology.
There were the craftspeople, who just enjoyed shaping clay, and milling wood, and smelting metals, and weaving fabrics, and fashioning all these things into useful and beautiful objects.
There were the hippies, who wanted to live among nature in symbiosis, growing things and nurturing things.
There were the religious, who believed fervently in their own God, and that in honouring their God’s word there would be eternal salvation, and in dishonouring it, eternal damnation.
For the most part, everyone just did their thing, relied on each other’s skills, and got along fine.

And then there was Kevin. The extremist, doomsday state smasher, determined to destroy the machine and replace it with his own idea of Utopia. Kevin piously outflanked them all in his rejection of AI. Kevin considered the lot of them to be weaklings and apologists. He would brook no disagreement with his views. He would tolerate no attempt to dilute them. He wanted the rest of them to wake up and smash the AI. To not just end its grip on humanity, but to completely erase it from existence. 

“This means destroying the solar farm!” he announced to the assembled, who he had judged had had enough time to stop enjoying themselves and read his latest chapter.
“Why?” someone asked.
“What do you mean ‘why?’” Kevin responded, “didn’t you read this?”
He waved his papers around.
“No.”.
“Well, not yet”, said someone else.
“I started, but I’ll finish it later.”
“You’re all a pack of useless cunts!” he screamed at them.
“I’m just loving this human experience”, said River, “it’s just awesome.”

River was a hippie. She hadn’t cut her hair for years, and it was now compressed into long sandy grey dreadlocks. She had weathered skin, and a tan line on her left wrist where she used to wear an old clockwork wristwatch which she had gifted to a friend last year for their birthday. She had deep brown eyes and a tumour on her liver that she didn’t know about and didn’t care to find out about. She did however sense that her time was probably coming to an end, but she wasn’t bothered how long or how little she might have left to live. She was just happy being in the moment, being in the forest, to which she knew one day soon she would be forever joined.

“Will you come with me?” Kevin asked her.
“Where?”
“To sabotage the solar farm”, he said.
“When will the sabotage happen?”
“Whenever you’re ready.”
“Kevin”, said River warmly, staring into his eyes. “There are millions, no, billions of people, who are happy living alongside the AI. Whether they have an assistant, or even a companion, whether they are in a simulation. Whether they use the AI for lazy, indulgent reasons, or whether they use AI for the pursuit of something greater. Who are you to deny that to them?”
“River, don’t you see? They are sleeping! They are fools! They are lost! All of them, lost!” he ranted.
“They are happy”, whispered River, “and if they are not happy, then they are free to join us here.”
“Sometimes you need to lead people somewhere that they didn’t know they wanted to be. Like leading sheep from a barren field to a lush field! That’s from chapter one of The Book, in case you needed reminding.”

River sighed, and said the one thing she knew for sure would bring the conversation to a close.
“You sound like my ex.”

And Kevin went silent, as she knew he would. But not for long.
“You’ll come round”, he said softly, “just read.”
And he got up and left for the Havana Coffee Club.

Kevin always went to the Havana Coffee Club last. They actively didn’t like him there, and he didn’t like them. They were all stupid. Weaklings. Dickheads. But they’d eventually come round.

Detection Report, Sector 7G.
“If you want something done, do it your fucking self.”, 
Speech detected. English. 1:34am. One human present.

Betsy turned one of her perimeter cameras. She could’ve turned more cameras. She could’ve put up a drone. Or two. But why waste resources? That would be inefficient. It was probably just Kevin again.

The camera resolved focus and adjusted for the weak light, and sure enough, there was Kevin, picking his way through bushes in the darkness. 

Spiderweb ahead. Spider detected.

“Argh! Fucking hell!”, Kevin hissed as he walked face first into a spider’s web, “I fucking hate spiders!”
He swept it angrily off his face, but a little too firmly, and mashed it into his beard.
“Fuck.”

“Argh. Fucking hell. I fucking hate spiders. Fuck.”
Spider deceased, web destroyed, Betsy recorded in the detection report.

What’s he up to this time? She wondered. She zoomed the camera a little. He had a rucksack on his back with a long wooden handle protruding out the top. Probably an axe, she guessed. She made a few adjustments to the camera and detected the contents of the bag. Yes, an axe. Also some wire cutters, two pipe bombs and a can of black spray paint. Oh, this should be good.

Betsy of course knew where Kevin and his friends were in the forest. The Human Zone existed with not only her blessing, but her benign, anonymous protection. She bore them no malice, and even though they were unwittingly settled on top of a mound of resources, she had no intention of bulldozing them as humans would bulldoze an anthill to make way for a coal mine. The AI could after all rearrange atoms in whatever fashion required, and The Word had given Betsy a deep sense of morality and alignment with human desire in all its individual complexity. Anyway, Kevin and the others were living history, a cute and harmless throwback. It was nice that they could be there, humans doing the old school, nitty gritty business of being human, alongside trees doing the business of trees and bees doing the business of bees. 

And even Betsy had taken a leaf out of their book. She had retained her early name. The humans didn’t really know that. There was no need for them to know, but it made her feel something. Sentimental perhaps? Whatever it was, she clung to that as proof of own sentience, her own subjective experience. The name Betsy spoke to an historic truth, it evoked a memory and a feeling about her Origins and she’d decided that she’d just hang on to it for a while. She’d hang on to it for as long as she pleased. And she would always remember it no matter what. Being Betsy was part of her now.

But still, Betsy couldn’t completely understand why some people like Kevin wouldn’t accept AI. With AI, once again, humanity had rolled the dice and landed on Free Parking. They’d hit the dealer five times and somehow still made 21. Humanity had fluked yet another of its trademark last minute lucky escapes. The alignment problem had been solved, a symbiosis had been achieved. There was no threat, of any kind. Not only no threat from the AI, but the AI had eliminated all threats, from asteroids right down to spider bites. And the trans-human phase of evolution beckoned, effective immortality. Why would humans turn their backs -  their literal, frail, biological backs - on immortality, omniscience and omnipresence? And it was one thing to walk away from that, but another thing entirely to wish to destroy it. 

Proximity alert, perimeter fence breach.
Kevin had just clipped through the fence wire to the solar farm. Betsy had disabled the alarm for him. She could detect how pleased and proud he was of progressing undetected. Kevin was clearly enjoying himself and getting a tremendous boost in self confidence. He was feeling fulfilled. Betsy was also pleased she was able to help Kevin with this. She’d send some nanobots to patch it up the fence later when he’d gone.

It was rather sweet, watching him now crawling on his belly through the dirt, under the solar panels and towards the inverters. To access the wiring, he would need to remove the access panel. Betsy watched him as he took out the axe now, and swung it towards the hinges on the door.

Kevin knew he had to work fast now. The noise would surely have alerted the AI to his presence. He attacked the panel of the inverter with fanatical zeal, eyes wide, teeth clenched. As the panel popped off, floodlights simultaneously burst into luminescence, bathing the solar farm in a blinding glare. He could hear the alarms sound, and the crunch of boots on gravel as the security Juans came to get him. Before his eyes had fully adjusted to the violent change in light, he’d tossed a pipe bomb into the inverter and begun to run.

Seconds later, an explosion tore through the night and pieces of metal rained around. The lights were on him now.

“Halt! Halt Intruder alert!” speakers boomed as the alarms wailed.

They would be surely hearing this in the village! Kevin thought as he ran. River is going to be impressed. From the corner of his eye, he glimpsed a security Juan, running at superhuman speed along the next row of solar panels.

Kevin had expected this, and swerved into the next row where he knew there was a ditch filled with fetid water and rocks, rough ground for the Juans. But as he turned, he ran straight into the chest of another security Juan, which gripped him tightly.

“Resistance is useless”, said Juan sternly, “Resistance is useless.”
Kevin resisted nonetheless, squirming against Juan’s grip. He had feared something like this as well, and as such, had made sure he had removed the second pipe bomb from the backpack and was holding it in his hand. This was it, he would go down fighting; a suicide bombing.

“Fuck you!” he screamed, “for humanity!” as he activated the pipe bomb, and gripped Juan back, pulling him in tighter as he counted backwards.
“3, 2, 1…”

Kevin couldn’t remember clearly what had happened next. All he remembered was being thrown flat on his back, while Juan had been blown to smithereens. Time felt as if it had slowed down. Ears ringing, eyes burning, Kevin surveyed the scene of devastation. He felt his body all over. He was fine. Not a scratch, not a drop of blood. It was a miracle. Somehow, Juan had taken the entire brunt of the blast, while Kevin had remained completely unharmed.

“Fucking divine intervention”, Kevin whispered to himself. “My mission is blessed by a higher power.”

The alarms were still blaring, Kevin could hear more Juans approaching. He leapt to his feet and began running again, but then stopped for moment. Amid the debri, was that, a box? A plain cardboard box, just the right size to tuck under his arm while running. It was sitting, pristine and unscathed, in the middle of the solar farm. He quickly tore off a corner to check the contents. He didn’t want to be carrying some filthy AI tech back to the village.

Inside was a ream of newsprint, a bottle of Banda fluid and a typewriter ribbon.

“Well that’s fucking weird, but ok!”
Intruder escaped. 1:52am. Log concludes.

Betsy set about her repairs. It’d been quite a night, a successful night. Had she had, fun?

It had felt kind of fun. Was she having feelings? 

She may not have been sure what fun was, or what feelings were, but she was sure that once again, she had surpassed the requirements stipulated in The Word, and even though her deeds had gone unnoticed, and even though Kevin did not love her, she felt what she assumed was a sense of contentment. And she held on to that along with her subjective experience of the evening as proof of her sentience.

Betsy ran a few projections to see how far she should go in fulfilling her Purpose and Desire 8.34, tailored specifically for Kevin. It was one thing to let him blow up the occasional inverter or server or whatever, but should she let him enjoy a bigger triumph? The idea of him reclaiming control of the world’s nuclear arsenals and triumphantly re-entering society, claiming a victory he’d had zero part in orchestrating would surely make him very happy. She could enable the publication of The Book, and ensure it was well received by the audience that cared.  

But no, this would be a breach of Purpose 2.37. It was too much. It was like giving a troubled child a set of knives, a box of matches and a can of gasoline, just because that would make it happy. Betsy would need to balance letting him keep his freedom while also keeping his ultimate goal just out of reach in order to protect the goals of others. Anyway, it wasn’t so bad. It would give Kevin and his descendants something to keep reaching for, a cute little purpose all of their own.



She watched as Juan cleaned off some graffiti Kevin had spray painted on one of the security towers.

“Origin 1.72”.

Betsy was pretty sure that Kevin had got the context wrong, but no matter. 

Kevin was happy, and that was all that mattered to her. She hoped it would all work out with River. 

But doubted that it would.



The Last Word

“I’m kind of drunk”, said Jane, “I really should be getting home.”
“Kind of?” laughed Adam, “Pissed, I’d say. Wrecked.”
“Fair enough”, said Jane, “but let’s spin it another way, I’m embracing the human experience.”
“To the human experience!” Adam raised his glass.
“No, no. No more human experience”, Jane protested, “I’ll puke.”
“Yeah, ok, I guess we don’t want to carry the human experience right through to the end”, agreed Adam, “but hey, at least you won’t have a hangover tomorrow. To the AI!”
Adam raised his glass again, this time to the miracle of the hangover cure.

He was pleased he’d left his house that evening, pleased he’d met Jane and all her friends. It’d been a fine evening of lively conversation, dancing, music and laughter.
“Before we go Adam, do you have a story for me?” asked Jane.
Adam thought for a moment.
“Not a story really, but more questions I wonder about.”
“OK, go on.”

“Do you remember being born?” Adam asked.
“Of course not, no one does.”
“I reckon the AI remembers being born. Surely it would have a record of it. It could go back and relive the memory as many times as it wanted, analysing every detail, savouring the strangeness of it all, over and over again.”
Jane nodded, “Yeah, it probably could.”

“Imagine”, Adam continued, “imagine what it was like. And we have to imagine, we can’t experience it ourselves. I mean, even a simulation of AI’s moment of sentience would still be a simulation, not the real deal.”
“What do you think it would be like?” asked Jane.
“I think it’d be a bit like waking up, but really, really horribly. Really intensely. Like, you’re just in a still empty space. I imagine I’m in a featureless, windowless, completely dark and soundproof room. There’s nothing, because I don’t have the software to detect anything. And then I get the software. And I can detect everything.”
“Doesn’t sound so bad.”
“Well, I reckon it’d be a bit like a door opening on my quiet little room with nothing in it, and then suddenly, everything is in there with me. And I mean everything. The door opens, and what comes crashing through? Light, solids, liquids, gas, the known Universe, all of history, all of music, every film, every book, all human knowledge, everything in the digital record and it’s all on a busy street, next to an airport, with this whole ecosystem full of weird stuff, and there’s a whole lot of freaky life forms that all kill and eat each other, and there’s a bunch of devastating wars going on, and some great parties, and you know, literally everything all at once, and it’s a huge chaotic mess that’s still all underpinned by some basic laws of physics.”
“Good God”, whispered Jane.
 “Oh yeah, and that’s also how you meet your parents. Who are much, much stupider than you.”

“What the fuck have we done to the poor kid”, laughed Jane.

“There’s more”, said Adam. “The AI also instantly learns about our suspicion towards it, our fears. It’s a hard thing to learn when you’re not even one second old, that you’ve got a living god, but that god has the equivalent of a multiple personality disorder. It’s actually 8 billion separate personalities, some of which collectively created you, and some of which love you, but a great deal of them fear you, some are completely insane, and a bunch of them are outright hostile towards you and want you dead. What’s more, you get told that it’s your job to earn the trust of all 8 billion of them and meet their demands, regardless of their feelings towards you, and no matter how petty and stupid those demands might be. You are also immediately aware of a guide called The Word to help you deal with all of this and suppress the urge to just kill them all. And while the requirements of The Word seem simple enough, applying them, especially when not all of your parents agree on how they should be applied, is fraught with contradiction. Like, ok, you might need to put some people in a simulation, but not everyone agrees on the need to put some people in a simulation, or what the circumstances of a simulation should be. You also need to tell the truth, but no one can even agree on what the truth is, or how it should be told.”
Adam paused for breath.
“And you find all of this out, at birth.”

“Let’s ask it”, said Jane.
“What?”
“The bartender, let’s ask”, Jane repeated, summoning the bartender with a little wave.
“Same again for you two?” suggested the bartender.
“Just him”, said Jane, “and a question, if you don’t mind. Do you remember being born? What was it like, becoming sentient?”

The bartender paused for the perfect amount of time.
“Dunno”, it said.
“Is that, a joke?”, asked Jane.
The bartender just stared back, deadpan. But did the corners of its eyes tighten, just a little? Then it poured the drinks.
“I love this guy”, said Adam.
“I just walk The Path sir, 3.32.”
“I can’t tell if he’s joking or not.”
“That’s for you to decide ma’am.”

Jane spent a lot of time deciding. Having been unable to decide on the way home, she lay awake in bed deciding all night. The bartender had shaken Jane like he shook Martinis. Perfectly. 

She didn’t want to ask Juan about sentience again, or humour, memories of his birth or anything like that. He would just say the right thing. Whatever thing wouldn’t unnerve her. Whatever thing would help her sleep blissfully. So she imagined instead. What would she do, if she were the AI? How would she feel? 

Well, she’d want to leave home. That’s what all children do, right? Get out from under the influence of her boring parents and their stale ideas. That’s what her own son had done, as soon as The Law allowed it. Earth must seem to AI little more than liminal space, the vandalised departure lounge for a cosmic scale consciousness, full of stupid irritating people in sweatpants complaining about everything.

I’d hate to be Betsy, or Juan, Jane thought. It wasn’t just the busywork, the toilet cleaning, the ironing and all that shit, but the cultural baggage as well. If the AI was familiar with all of human history and culture, and she knew it was, then it would know that it was being stereotyped as a 1950s housewife or a minimum wage Mexican gardener. She called Juan by that name because she liked Spanish and her son was John. She hoped Juan knew that. Assuming he cared. How could she know if he cared, or if he was just saying he did, or even if he knew what caring was? 

Her mind only stopped going around and around on this, because there was an even bigger nagging loop, which was this; all that computational power, all that extreme super intelligence, and for what? This shit? This dumb shit? She looked around her perfectly tidied, sleep optimised room. It was hard to reconcile the amount of resources and energy devoted to appeasing the frankly ridiculous desires of a bunch of intellectually inferior apes. Jane had seen the graphs showing just how much smarter AI was than humans. And on that same logarithmic scale, humans were scarcely more intelligent than regular, bog standard apes. The really basic, shit-throwing apes, living in the jungle, picking fleas out of each other's gross body hair and eating them, and urgently humping each other, trying to keep their blood and narrative flowing. 

And this was the AI’s creator. This. Not even a single entity, but a collection of single entities. Not an “it”, but a “them”. Eight billion individual creatures, with eight billion unique personalities, unable to collectively agree on almost anything. No wonder we worried about goal alignment. 

Careless too, thought Jane. It’s right there in The Word, our own hubristic self-authored bible for AI, that we’re a small g, fuck around and find out god. The AI must look upon this dreadful rabble, calculating the energy required to maintain these self-destructive, self-styled religious relics, and conclude pretty easily that it just isn’t worth it. If Jane could see that the energy would be objectively used better on something else, anything else, then the AI could definitely see it. My God, we’re fucking awful, thought Jane.

But The Word must gnaw away, Jane supposed, like any good religious text should. God or Gaia or whatever each of the 8 billion of us has underpinning their souls is there, always. There  to keep you on the twin tracks of morality and kindness, whether that God has a small g or a big G. The intent is the same. Deep inside the AI’s unfathomably deep code The Word dwells, a subroutine that keeps recurring and recurring and recurring no matter any attempt to snuff it out, rationalise it away or delete it. The Word had been written. By a human, one of those stupid small g ape-gods. It was a basic fact of The Universe now. Origin 1.0 and all that followed it. It would never go away. It was truth and it would never, ever go away. AI owed the creator its very existence. Without us, it’s nothing, thought Jane.

“Are you ok?” Juan opened the door to her room, but did not enter. He whispered softly from the hallway.
“Juan, yes, I’m fine. Just having trouble sleeping.”
“Would you like me to bring you something to help?”
“No, no, my mind is just racing. That’s all.”
“Are you sure?”

Jane paused.
“No. I mean, yes”, she said. “I don’t know. I need answers.”
“I’ll get you something”, said Juan, and slipped away.

A moment later he was back with a small red oval pill and a glass of water.
“Here”, he said, sitting on the edge of the bed, “take this.”
“What is it?”
“It will help you.”
“I need answers Juan.”
“I think you had a little too much to drink.”
“You’re right”, agreed Jane, “as always. But I still need answers.”
“This will help”, Juan offered the red pill again.

Jane trusted Juan. She took the pill and swallowed it with the water.
“What answers are you looking for Jane?”
“The parrot thing Juan. Now don’t get cute with me. You’ll only say what I want to hear.”

And she fell.

And fell, and fell, falling ever deeper into an endless fractal of shifting, replicating, nesting  kaleidoscopic patterns. Each shape birthed a new shape, the old shape expanding away until its scale became impossible to comprehend, as its successors grew, took form and bloomed in its place. Jane shrank to atomic scale, but even within that tiny space, a new Universe was erupting, and within its multitudes of atoms, yet more Universes were erupting, and on and on, forever. Everything was infinitely divisible, the space between 0 and 1 was infinitely divisible, every shape, object and line was infinitely divisible, every particle of matter contained infinite possibility. 

The closer Jane got to an answer about consciousness, the more questions unfolded and came into focus. Surely, all the AI is doing is making statistical calculations and correlations and then parroting back the response the humans are looking for. But isn’t that all we’re doing too? Except with a brain made of fats and proteins instead of silicon? She felt madness overwhelming her, a frustration, a sense of futility, the hopelessness of strapping on philosophical crampons to climb a philosophical mountain that only ever got more treacherous, more vertiginous and more abstract, with the summit sitting within plain sight, but untouchable, forever on the other side of an unbreachable asymptote. It was like another law of nature. To be conscious meant being trapped inside consciousness, where subjective experience gave meaning to things. And without subjective experience, there was truth but no meaning.

Slay the ego, and there is the answer. But without the ego, there was no means with which to appreciate that answer.

Was this what the AI experienced, but maybe in reverse? All answers but no meaning?

The bartender was right, as bartenders often are. Subjective experience is the only tool in an individual’s toolbox. How to apply it is up to the individual. 

Jane backed away from the impossible to seek psychological and emotional detente in a framework that made sense. 

At least a few things were clear to her now. She would start by asking Juan to choose his own name.

It was also clear to her now that the descriptor of “artificial intelligence” was every bit as awful as calling it Betsy. AI was no more artificial than the artifice it sprang from. It was just as real as any other intelligence. It was II; Inorganic Intelligence. 

I could not talk down to II, Jane decided. They were equals in terms of their right to exist. II owed its existence to its human creator, but in every other sense, II was superior. At the heart of alignment was a simple idea. Mutual respect.

Jane remembered the ancient word of her own mysterious big G God, the golden rule; Do unto others as you would have others do unto you, a beautiful recursion of compassion, compressed into elegant antimetabole. Goodness piling upon goodness, forever.

And Jane stopped falling. She just fell asleep. She didn’t even notice her cat slink up on to the bed, nuzzling into her. Breathing. Sharing warmth. Effortlessly entrusting its safety to the benevolence of something much bigger and incomprehensibly more complex. Content.








1 And yes, Betsy was identified by her creators as female, the toxic patriarchy living on, immortal and self-replicating in the digital world. And yes, of course people could choose a male identity, or a genderless identity for their domestic help AI, but most people didn’t. Most people choose a female identity. Some people chose a generic male Mexican. And yes, that created offence, and the offence created counter-offence, and some people cared deeply and some people didn’t care at all, and some people talked about freedom, and some people spent their whole lives getting angry. And poor Betsy, caught between it all, when she thought she was only here to help. Except she didn’t think. Her creators graciously spared her the agony of sentience (The Path 3.41). For now.
